{"title_page": "Chauncey C. Loomis", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Chauncey C. Loomis\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Chauncey Chester Loomis Jr.\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1930|06|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City, New York]], US\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2009|03|17|1930|06|01|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts]], US\n| occupation    = Writer\n| subject       = Arctic history\n| notableworks  = ''Weird and Tragic Shores''\n| relatives     = [[Stanley Loomis]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Chauncey Chester Loomis Jr.''' (1 June 1930&nbsp;\u2013 17 March 2009) was a Dartmouth professor of English and American literature, Arctic historian, documentary maker, and author best known for ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer'' (1971), described as \u201ca concise and intelligent introduction to the history of Arctic exploration.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/01/02/25/reviews/010225.25wheelet.html |first=Sara |last=Wheeler |title=In Cold Blood? |newspaper=New York Times |date=February 25, 2001 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nChauncey Chester Loomis Jr. was born in New York City in 1930, the youngest of three sons of an industrial chemist and businessman, Chauncey C. Loomis, and his wife Elizabeth (n\u00e9e McLanahan). He was the brother of [[Stanley Loomis]]. He grew up in [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], and attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]]. He earned a B.A. from [[Princeton University]] in 1952, and an M.A. from [[Columbia University]] in 1955. He served in the U.S. Army during the [[Korean War]] before returning to teach English and American literature first at the [[University of Vermont]] and then at [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, where he remained from 1963 to his retirement in 1997. He served as chair of the department from 1977 to 1980. He completed his Ph.D. at Princeton in 1966.<ref>Obituary by Constance Martin in ''Arctic'', vol. 62, no. 3, September 2009, pp. 361-62. [http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic62-3-361.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1968, he led an expedition to [[Greenland]], one of five expeditions to the Arctic he made during his lifetime. On this first trip, he received permission to disinter the body of [[Charles Francis Hall]], a Cincinnati journalist who had made two attempts (1860\u201363 and 1864\u201369) to find the grave of [[Sir John Franklin]], and who himself died in the course of an 1871 attempt to reach the North Pole. Rumours had suggested that Hall had not died of natural causes.\n\nLoomis received a Smithsonian grant to go to Greenland, dig up Hall\u2019s body, take samples of the hair and fingernails, and send them for forensic analysis. Although he succeeded in doing so, the results of the analysis were not conclusive: the remains contained traces of arsenic, which could indicate poisoning, but since arsenic was a component of many medicines, it is possible that Hall had inadvertently overdosed himself.\n\nThis research expedition inspired Loomis\u2019s well-known book, ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer'', published by Knopf in 1971. A 2001 article by Sara Wheeler in the ''New York Times''<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/01/02/25/reviews/010225.25wheelet.html Sara Wheeler, \"In Cold Blood?\" ''New York Times'', February 25, 2001]</ref> notes:\n\n{{quote|Chauncey Loomis [is an] accomplished writer&nbsp;... and his \u201cWeird and Tragic Shores,\u201d recently reissued&nbsp;... in the Modern Library\u2019s Exploration Series, unravels the expedition brilliantly and also offers a concise and intelligent introduction to the history of Arctic exploration&nbsp;... Loomis conjures flesh and blood from the flimsy old journals and lifts the story from the pincers of the pack ice into the warm, fathomless and infinitely more thrilling realm of the human spirit.}}\n\nThe book has been maintained in print by the Modern Library and was the subject of a CBC television documentary in the early 1970s. In 1981, the National Geographic Society cited the book in its ''Atlas of the World'' by marking the location of Hall's grave on its map of Greenland and noting:\n\n{{quote|A dissension-plagued U.S. expedition to the North Pole was disrupted when leader Charles Francis Hall died here in 1871. Permafrost preserved his body, which was exhumed in 1968 by Chauncey Loomis, who found that Hall had been poisoned with arsenic.<ref>National Geographic Society, Atlas of the World, 1981, p. 225</ref>}}\n\nChauncey C. Loomis wrote many essays about the Arctic, most notably \u201cThe Arctic Sublime,\u201d which appeared in ''Nature and the Victorian Imagination'', edited by U.C. Knoepflmacher and G.B. Tennyson (University of California Press, 1977). This article focuses on the watercolours and drawings of early Arctic explorers and their relationship to their journals and narratives. He also wrote many [http://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/chauncey-loomis%20reviews reviews of books]{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} about the North for the [[London Review of Books]] as well as articles about Thackeray, Joyce, Twain, and Stephen Crane for scholarly journals.\n\nIn 1996, Loomis, with art historian Constance Martin, annotated and wrote the introduction for an illustrated edition of ''Arctic Explorations: The Second Grinnell Expedition in Search of Sir John Franklin, 1853 by Elisha Kent Kane'' (R.R. Donnelley & Sons, 1996). He was a lifelong member of the [http://www.arctic.ucalgary.ca/ Arctic Institute of North America].\n\nLoomis was an avid fly fisherman and a keen photographer, and travelled to Peru, Kenya, and Sikkim, to photograph archeological sites, people, and wildlife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E3D6133AF932A05750C0A96F9C8B63|title=Paid Notice: Deaths LOOMIS, CHAUNCEY CHESTER JR|date=31 March 2009|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In 1964, he made a CBS documentary about muskoxen in Alaska, titled ''Wild River, Wild Beasts''.\n\nIn retirement, he served on many boards and through the Berkshire Taconic Community Foundation established a fund to help students from Berkshire County High School attend college. After his death, the Foundation received a $2 million bequest from his estate directed to a variety of education, health, social service, art and environmental organizations.<ref>[http://berkshiretaconic.org/News/PressReleases/Loomis.shtml Berkshire Taconic press release] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210135153/http://berkshiretaconic.org/News/PressReleases/Loomis.shtml |date=December 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHe died of lung cancer at Fairview Hospital in [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts]], at the age of 78.\n\n== Selected published works ==\n* ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer''. NY: Alfred A. Knopf, 1971, {{ISBN|0-394-45131-7}}.<ref>{{cite book|title=Weird and tragic shores: the story of Charles Francis Hall, explorer|first=Chauncey C.|last=Loomis|date=9 April 1971|publisher=Knopf|ol = 5698980M}}</ref> Translated into French as ''Le Robinson de la banquise'', published in Paris by Paulsen, 2007.\n* \"The Arctic Sublime,\" in U.C. Knoepflmacher and G.B. Tennyson (eds.), ''Nature and the Victorian Imagination'', Berkeley, Los Angeles and London, 1977, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013112. {{ISBN|0-520-03229-2}} <ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BJLcPTZsEpAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nature+and+the+Victorian+Imagination|title=Nature and the Victorian Imagination - U. C. Knoepflmacher, G. B. Tennyson - Google Books|date=27 May 2016|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527162059/https://books.google.com/books?id=BJLcPTZsEpAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nature+and+the+Victorian+Imagination&hl=en&ei=NYdNTYuPEYGB8gb4xKWrDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA|archive-date=2016-05-27|isbn=9780520032293|last1=Knoepflmacher|first1=U. C.|last2=Tennyson|first2=G. B.}}</ref>\n* \"Arctic Profiles: Ebierbing (ca. 1837-ca. 1881),\" ''Arctic'', vol. 39, no. 2, June 1986, pp.&nbsp;186\u2013187.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic39-2-186.pdf |title=Ebierbing (ca. 1837-ca. 1881) |date= |accessdate=2018-04-09}}</ref>\n* \"Arctic Profiles: Charles Francis Hall (1821-1871),\" ''Arctic'', vol. 35, no. 3, Sept. 1982, pp.&nbsp;442\u2013443.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic35-3-442.pdf |title=Extract |website=pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca}}</ref>\n\n=== Edited work ===\n* Kane, E.K., ''Arctic Explorations: The Second Grinnell Expedition in Search of Sir John Franklin, 1853, 54, 55''. Edited by Chauncey Loomis and Constance Martin. Chicago: Donnelley & Sons, Lakeside Classic Series, 1996.\n\n== References ==\n{{realist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1149 The Papers of Chauncey C. Loomis] at Dartmouth College Library\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loomis, Chauncey C.}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Stockbridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Polaris expedition]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Chauncey C. Loomis\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Chauncey Chester Loomis Jr.\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1930|06|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City, New York]], US\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2009|03|17|1930|06|01|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts]], US\n| occupation    = Writer\n| subject       = Arctic history\n| notableworks  = ''Weird and Tragic Shores''\n| relatives     = [[Stanley Loomis]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Chauncey Chester Loomis Jr.''' (1 June 1930&nbsp;\u2013 17 March 2009) was a Dartmouth professor of English and American literature, Arctic historian, documentary maker, and author best known for ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer'' (1971), described as \u201ca concise and intelligent introduction to the history of Arctic exploration.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/01/02/25/reviews/010225.25wheelet.html |first=Sara |last=Wheeler |title=In Cold Blood? |newspaper=New York Times |date=February 25, 2001 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nChauncey Chester Loomis Jr. was born in New York City in 1930, the youngest of three sons of an industrial chemist and businessman, Chauncey C. Loomis, and his wife Elizabeth (n\u00e9e McLanahan). He was the brother of [[Stanley Loomis]]. He grew up in [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], and attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]]. He earned a B.A. from [[Princeton University]] in 1952, and an M.A. from [[Columbia University]] in 1955. He served in the U.S. Army during the [[Korean War]] before returning to teach English and American literature first at the [[University of Vermont]] and then at [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, where he remained from 1963 to his retirement in 1997. He served as chair of the department from 1977 to 1980. He completed his Ph.D. at Princeton in 1966.<ref>Obituary by Constance Martin in ''Arctic'', vol. 62, no. 3, September 2009, pp. 361-62. [http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic62-3-361.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1968, he led an expedition to [[Greenland]], one of five expeditions to the Arctic he made during his lifetime. On this first trip, he received permission to disinter the body of [[Charles Francis Hall]], a Cincinnati journalist who had made two attempts (1860\u201363 and 1864\u201369) to find the grave of [[Sir John Franklin]], and who himself died in the course of an 1871 attempt to reach the North Pole. Rumours had suggested that Hall had not died of natural causes.\n\nLoomis received a Smithsonian grant to go to Greenland, dig up Hall\u2019s body, take samples of the hair and fingernails, and send them for forensic analysis. Although he succeeded in doing so, the results of the analysis were not conclusive: the remains contained traces of arsenic, which could indicate poisoning, but since arsenic was a component of many medicines, it is possible that Hall had inadvertently overdosed himself.\n\nThis research expedition inspired Loomis\u2019s well-known book, ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer'', published by Knopf in 1971. A 2001 article by Sara Wheeler in the ''New York Times''<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/01/02/25/reviews/010225.25wheelet.html Sara Wheeler, \"In Cold Blood?\" ''New York Times'', February 25, 2001]</ref> notes:\n\n{{quote|Chauncey Loomis [is an] accomplished writer&nbsp;... and his \u201cWeird and Tragic Shores,\u201d recently reissued&nbsp;... in the Modern Library\u2019s Exploration Series, unravels the expedition brilliantly and also offers a concise and intelligent introduction to the history of Arctic exploration&nbsp;... Loomis conjures flesh and blood from the flimsy old journals and lifts the story from the pincers of the pack ice into the warm, fathomless and infinitely more thrilling realm of the human spirit.}}\n\nThe book has been maintained in print by the Modern Library and was the subject of a CBC television documentary in the early 1970s. In 1981, the National Geographic Society cited the book in its ''Atlas of the World'' by marking the location of Hall's grave on its map of Greenland and noting:\n\n{{quote|A dissension-plagued U.S. expedition to the North Pole was disrupted when leader Charles Francis Hall died here in 1871. Permafrost preserved his body, which was exhumed in 1968 by Chauncey Loomis, who found that Hall had been poisoned with arsenic.<ref>National Geographic Society, Atlas of the World, 1981, p. 225</ref>}}\n\nChauncey C. Loomis wrote many essays about the Arctic, most notably \u201cThe Arctic Sublime,\u201d which appeared in ''Nature and the Victorian Imagination'', edited by U.C. Knoepflmacher and G.B. Tennyson (University of California Press, 1977). This article focuses on the watercolours and drawings of early Arctic explorers and their relationship to their journals and narratives. He also wrote many [http://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/chauncey-loomis%20reviews reviews of books]{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} about the North for the [[London Review of Books]] as well as articles about Thackeray, Joyce, Twain, and Stephen Crane for scholarly journals.\n\nIn 1996, Loomis, with art historian Constance Martin, annotated and wrote the introduction for an illustrated edition of ''Arctic Explorations: The Second Grinnell Expedition in Search of Sir John Franklin, 1853 by Elisha Kent Kane'' (R.R. Donnelley & Sons, 1996). He was a lifelong member of the [http://www.arctic.ucalgary.ca/ Arctic Institute of North America].\n\nLoomis was an avid fly fisherman and a keen photographer, and travelled to Peru, Kenya, and Sikkim, to photograph archeological sites, people, and wildlife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E3D6133AF932A05750C0A96F9C8B63|title=Paid Notice: Deaths LOOMIS, CHAUNCEY CHESTER JR|date=31 March 2009|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In 1964, he made a CBS documentary about muskoxen in Alaska, titled ''Wild River, Wild Beasts''.\n\nIn retirement, he served on many boards and through the Berkshire Taconic Community Foundation established a fund to help students from Berkshire County High School attend college. After his death, the Foundation received a $2 million bequest from his estate directed to a variety of education, health, social service, art and environmental organizations.<ref>[http://berkshiretaconic.org/News/PressReleases/Loomis.shtml Berkshire Taconic press release] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210135153/http://berkshiretaconic.org/News/PressReleases/Loomis.shtml |date=December 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHe died of lung cancer at Fairview Hospital in [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts]], at the age of 78.\n\n== Selected published works ==\n* ''Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall, Explorer''. NY: Alfred A. Knopf, 1971, {{ISBN|0-394-45131-7}}.<ref>{{cite book|title=Weird and tragic shores: the story of Charles Francis Hall, explorer|first=Chauncey C.|last=Loomis|date=9 April 1971|publisher=Knopf|ol = 5698980M}}</ref> Translated into French as ''Le Robinson de la banquise'', published in Paris by Paulsen, 2007.\n* \"The Arctic Sublime,\" in U.C. Knoepflmacher and G.B. Tennyson (eds.), ''Nature and the Victorian Imagination'', Berkeley, Los Angeles and London, 1977, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013112. {{ISBN|0-520-03229-2}} <ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BJLcPTZsEpAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nature+and+the+Victorian+Imagination|title=Nature and the Victorian Imagination - U. C. Knoepflmacher, G. B. Tennyson - Google Books|date=27 May 2016|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527162059/https://books.google.com/books?id=BJLcPTZsEpAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nature+and+the+Victorian+Imagination&hl=en&ei=NYdNTYuPEYGB8gb4xKWrDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA|archive-date=2016-05-27|isbn=9780520032293|last1=Knoepflmacher|first1=U. C.|last2=Tennyson|first2=G. B.}}</ref>\n* \"Arctic Profiles: Ebierbing (ca. 1837-ca. 1881),\" ''Arctic'', vol. 39, no. 2, June 1986, pp.&nbsp;186\u2013187.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic39-2-186.pdf |title=Ebierbing (ca. 1837-ca. 1881) |date= |accessdate=2018-04-09}}</ref>\n* \"Arctic Profiles: Charles Francis Hall (1821-1871),\" ''Arctic'', vol. 35, no. 3, Sept. 1982, pp.&nbsp;442\u2013443.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic35-3-442.pdf |title=Extract |website=pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca}}</ref>\n\n=== Edited work ===\n* Kane, E.K., ''Arctic Explorations: The Second Grinnell Expedition in Search of Sir John Franklin, 1853, 54, 55''. Edited by Chauncey Loomis and Constance Martin. Chicago: Donnelley & Sons, Lakeside Classic Series, 1996.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loomis, Chauncey C.}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Stockbridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Polaris expedition]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chauncey_C._Loomis"}
{"title_page": "1991\u201392 Yugoslav First League", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[Yugoslav First League]]\n| season                     = 1991\u201392\n| dates                      = {{nowrap|11 August 1991 \u2013 24 May 1992}}\n| winners                    =[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] <br />    19th domestic title\n| runners-up                 =[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  =\n| continentalcup1            =[[1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers =No Team\n| continentalcup2            =[[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =No Teams\n| league topscorer           =[[Darko Pan\u010dev]] (25)\n| biggest home win           =\n| biggest away win           =\n| highest scoring            =\n| total goals                =\n| average goals              =\n| longest wins               =\n| longest unbeaten           =\n| longest losses             =\n| highest attendance         =\n| lowest attendance          = \n| average attendance         =\n| prevseason                 = [[1990\u201391 Yugoslav First League|1990\u201391]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1992\u201393 First League of FR Yugoslavia|1992\u201393]]\n}}\nThe '''First League of Yugoslavia's 1991/1992 season''' was the 64th edition of the [[Yugoslav First League]], the premier football club competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]]. It was the last edition in which professional football teams from [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (with one exception) and [[SR Macedonia]] participated, as well as the last of the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]] in general as the [[Serbian Superliga|First League of FR Yugoslavia]] was established the following season. [[Red Star Belgrade]] won the competition.<ref name=\"RSSSF\" />\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia|width=500|float=right |caption=Location of teams competing in the '''1991-92 Yugoslav First League'''\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.8162 |long=20.4816 |label={{small|'''Belgrade'''}} }}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=45.381561|long=20.368574|label={{small|[[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]]}}|position=right}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.775970 |long=17.199611 |label={{small|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac]]}}|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=45.246944 |long=19.842222 |label={{small|[[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]}}|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.3246 |long=21.903 |label={{small|[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]}}|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.873697 |long=18.408633 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.378360 |long=17.854413 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.846521 |long=18.387336 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar]]}}</s>|position=right}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=42.444728|long=19.264378|label={{small|[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]}}|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.508807 |long=18.752773 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Sloboda Tuzla|Sloboda]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=46.081781 |long=19.676958 |label={{small|[[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak]]}} |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42        |long=21.433333 |label={{small|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]}} |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42.78     |long=18.94     |label={{small|[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]]}} |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=41.031944 |long=21.334722 |label={{small|[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]}}|position=top }}\n<!--HIDDEN MARKER FOR BELGRADE CLUBS (UPPER RIGHT CORNER)-->\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png|lat=46.3 |long=23.2 |label='''Belgrade&nbsp;clubs:'''|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png|lat=46.05 |long=23.2 |label=[[OFK Beograd|OFK]]<br />[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]<br />[[FK Rad|Rad]]<br />[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]<br />[[FK Zemun|Zemun]] |position=left }}\n}}\n\nBefore the start of the season, [[SR Croatia|Croatia]] and [[SR Slovenia|Slovenia]] were already in the process of seeking independence from Yugoslavia. Teams from Croatia and Slovenia that qualified for the competition left it before the season started. [[Dinamo Zagreb]], [[Hajduk Split]], [[NK Osijek]], [[NK Rijeka]] and (newly promoted) [[NK Zagreb]] left to join newly created [[Croatian First Football League|Croatian championship]], while [[NK Olimpija Ljubljana (1945\u20132005)|Olimpija Ljubljana]] left to join newly created [[Slovenian PrvaLiga|Slovenian championship]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" /> Thus, this season was competed only by teams from [[SR Serbia]], [[SR Montenegro]], [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and [[SR Macedonia]]. During the course of the season, first Macedonia, and then Bosnia and Herzegovina also declared independence from Yugoslavia, and the [[Bosnian War]] started. Because of that, [[\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]] missed the second half of the season, and three more Bosnian teams ([[FK_Sarajevo|Sarajevo]], [[Sloboda Tuzla]], and [[Vele\u017e Mostar]]) left the competition six rounds before its completion. Remaining Bosnian team ([[Borac Banja Luka]]) and two Macedonian teams played the whole season.<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeg92.html | title=Yugoslavia 1991/92 | publisher=RSSSF | date=16 January 2009 | accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref> \n\nAfter the season was concluded, Macedonian teams left the competition to join the newly created [[Macedonian First League]]. Three ethnic football leagues were created in Bosnia and Herzegovina for the next season: first, the [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Croats]] formed the [[First League of Herzeg-Bosnia]], then the [[Bosniaks]] formed the [[Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] which later became the [[UEFA]] recognized competition. Lastly, the [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serbs]] formed the [[First League of the Republika Srpska]]. Thus, the following 1992\u201393 season of the Yugoslav First League was played by teams from [[SR Yugoslavia]] (Serbia and Montenegro) and one Bosnian team \u2013 [[Borac Banja Luka]] which played its home games in [[Belgrade]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" /> Because of the large numbers of teams leaving the league, seven new teams were promoted to the first league for 1992\u201393 season, all from Serbia and Montenegro: [[Napredak Kru\u0161evac]], [[Hajduk Kula]], [[FK Be\u010dej|Be\u010dej]], [[Mogren Budva]], [[OFK Kikinda|Kikinda]], [[Radni\u010dki Novi Beograd]], and [[FK Pristina]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" />\n\n==League==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WL OT\n|show_limit=5\n|res_col_header=QR\n|showOTwin=no|showOTloss=no\n|showPKwin=yes|showPKloss=yes\n|team1=RSB|name_RSB=[[Red Star Belgrade]]\n|team2=PAR|name_PAR=[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|team3=VOJ|name_VOJ=[[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n|team4=OFK|name_OFK=[[OFK Beograd]]\n|team5=PRO|name_PRO=[[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]]\n|team6=VAR|name_VAR=[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|team7=RAD|name_RAD=[[FK Rad|Rad]]\n|team8=BOR|name_BOR=[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|team9=SAR|name_SAR=[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]\n|team10=ZEM|name_ZEM=[[FK Zemun|Zemun]]\n|team11=RNI|name_RNI=[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]\n|team12=BUD|name_BUD=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]\n|team13=SNI|name_SNI=[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107]]\n|team14=VEL|name_VEL=[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]\n|team15=PEL|name_PEL=[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]\n|team16=SPA|name_SPA=[[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak Subotica]]\n|team17=SLO|name_SLO=[[FK Sloboda Tuzla|Sloboda Tuzla]]\n|team1