ag Mijatovi\u0107]]\n|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Ljubinko Drulovi\u0107]]\n|[[FK Rad|Rad]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|7\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Slobodan Kr\u010dmarevi\u0107]]\n|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|rowspan=2 align=center|11\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Milenko \u0160poljari\u0107]]\n|[[OFK Beograd]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4 align=center|9\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} {{flagicon|MKD|1992}} [[Vasil Gunev]]\n|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|rowspan=4 align=center|10\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Dragan \u0110ukanovi\u0107]]\n|[[OFK Beograd]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Ljubi\u0161a Milojevi\u0107]]\n|[[FK Rad|Rad]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Dejan Petkovi\u0107]]\n|[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1991\u201392 Yugoslav Second League]]\n*[[1991\u201392 Yugoslav Cup]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Yugoslav First League}}\n{{Succession of Yugoslav First League}}\n{{1991\u201392 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1991-92 Yugoslav First League}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1991\u201392 in European association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1991\u201392 in Yugoslavian football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[Yugoslav First League]]\n| season                     = 1991\u201392\n| dates                      = {{nowrap|11 August 1991 \u2013 24 May 1992}}\n| winners                    =[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] <br />    19th domestic title\n| runners-up                 =[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  =\n| continentalcup1            =[[1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers =No Team\n| continentalcup2            =[[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =No Teams\n| league topscorer           =[[Darko Pan\u010dev]] (25)\n| biggest home win           =\n| biggest away win           =\n| highest scoring            =\n| total goals                =\n| average goals              =\n| longest wins               =\n| longest unbeaten           =\n| longest losses             =\n| highest attendance         =\n| lowest attendance          = \n| average attendance         =\n| prevseason                 = [[1990\u201391 Yugoslav First League|1990\u201391]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1992\u201393 First League of FR Yugoslavia|1992\u201393]]\n}}\nThe '''First League of Yugoslavia's 1991/1992 season''' was the 64th edition of the [[Yugoslav First League]], the premier football club competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]]. It was the last edition in which professional football teams from [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (with one exception) and [[SR Macedonia]] participated, as well as the last of the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]] in general as the [[Serbian Superliga|First League of FR Yugoslavia]] was established the following season. [[Red Star Belgrade]] won the competition.<ref name=\"RSSSF\" />\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia|width=500|float=right |caption=Location of teams competing in the '''1991-92 Yugoslav First League'''\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.8162 |long=20.4816 |label={{small|'''Belgrade'''}} }}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=45.381561|long=20.368574|label={{small|[[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]]}}|position=right}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.775970 |long=17.199611 |label={{small|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac]]}}|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=45.246944 |long=19.842222 |label={{small|[[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]}}|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.3246 |long=21.903 |label={{small|[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]}}|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.873697 |long=18.408633 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.378360 |long=17.854413 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=43.846521 |long=18.387336 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar]]}}</s>|position=right}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=42.444728|long=19.264378|label={{small|[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]}}|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=44.508807 |long=18.752773 |label=<s>{{small|[[FK Sloboda Tuzla|Sloboda]]}}</s>|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|lat=46.081781 |long=19.676958 |label={{small|[[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak]]}} |position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42        |long=21.433333 |label={{small|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]}} |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42.78     |long=18.94     |label={{small|[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]]}} |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=41.031944 |long=21.334722 |label={{small|[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]}}|position=top }}\n<!--HIDDEN MARKER FOR BELGRADE CLUBS (UPPER RIGHT CORNER)-->\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png|lat=46.3 |long=23.2 |label='''Belgrade&nbsp;clubs:'''|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Yugoslavia|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png|lat=46.05 |long=23.2 |label=[[OFK Beograd|OFK]]<br />[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]<br />[[FK Rad|Rad]]<br />[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]<br />[[FK Zemun|Zemun]] |position=left }}\n}}\n\nBefore the start of the season, [[SR Croatia|Croatia]] and [[SR Slovenia|Slovenia]] were already in the process of seeking independence from Yugoslavia. Teams from Croatia and Slovenia that qualified for the competition left it before the season started. [[Dinamo Zagreb]], [[Hajduk Split]], [[NK Osijek]], [[NK Rijeka]] and (newly promoted) [[NK Zagreb]] left to join newly created [[Croatian First Football League|Croatian championship]], while [[NK Olimpija Ljubljana (1945\u20132005)|Olimpija Ljubljana]] left to join newly created [[Slovenian PrvaLiga|Slovenian championship]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" /> Thus, this season was competed only by teams from [[SR Serbia]], [[SR Montenegro]], [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and [[SR Macedonia]]. During the course of the season, first Macedonia, and then Bosnia and Herzegovina also declared independence from Yugoslavia, and the [[Bosnian War]] started. Because of that, [[\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]] missed the second half of the season, and three more Bosnian teams ([[FK_Sarajevo|Sarajevo]], [[Sloboda Tuzla]], and [[Vele\u017e Mostar]]) left the competition six rounds before its completion. Remaining Bosnian team ([[Borac Banja Luka]]) and two Macedonian teams played the whole season.<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeg92.html | title=Yugoslavia 1991/92 | publisher=RSSSF | date=16 January 2009 | accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref> \n\nAfter the season was concluded, Macedonian teams left the competition to join the newly created [[Macedonian First League]]. Three ethnic football leagues were created in Bosnia and Herzegovina for the next season: first, the [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Croats]] formed the [[First League of Herzeg-Bosnia]], then the [[Bosniaks]] formed the [[Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] which later became the [[UEFA]] recognized competition. Lastly, the [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serbs]] formed the [[First League of the Republika Srpska]]. Thus, the following 1992\u201393 season of the Yugoslav First League was played by teams from [[SR Yugoslavia]] (Serbia and Montenegro) and one Bosnian team \u2013 [[Borac Banja Luka]] which played its home games in [[Belgrade]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" /> Because of the large numbers of teams leaving the league, seven new teams were promoted to the first league for 1992\u201393 season, all from Serbia and Montenegro: [[Napredak Kru\u0161evac]], [[Hajduk Kula]], [[FK Be\u010dej|Be\u010dej]], [[Mogren Budva]], [[OFK Kikinda|Kikinda]], [[Radni\u010dki Novi Beograd]], and [[FK Pristina]].<ref name=\"RSSSF\" />\n\n==League==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WL OT\n|show_limit=5\n|res_col_header=QR\n|showOTwin=no|showOTloss=no\n|showPKwin=yes|showPKloss=yes\n|team1=RSB|name_RSB=[[Red Star Belgrade]]\n|team2=PAR|name_PAR=[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|team3=VOJ|name_VOJ=[[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n|team4=OFK|name_OFK=[[OFK Beograd]]\n|team5=PRO|name_PRO=[[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]]\n|team6=VAR|name_VAR=[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|team7=RAD|name_RAD=[[FK Rad|Rad]]\n|team8=BOR|name_BOR=[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|team9=SAR|name_SAR=[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]\n|team10=ZEM|name_ZEM=[[FK Zemun|Zemun]]\n|team11=RNI|name_RNI=[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]\n|team12=BUD|name_BUD=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]\n|team13=SNI|name_SNI=[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107]]\n|team14=VEL|name_VEL=[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]\n|team15=PEL|name_PEL=[[FK Pelister|Pelister]]\n|team16=SPA|name_SPA=[[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak Subotica]]\n|team17=SLO|name_SLO=[[FK Sloboda Tuzla|Sloboda Tuzla]]\n|team18=\u017dEL|name_\u017dEL=[[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar]]\n|win_RSB=23|PKwin_RSB=4|PKloss_RSB=1|loss_RSB=5|gf_RSB=77|ga_RSB=24|status_RSB=C\n|win_PAR=21|PKwin_PAR=4|PKloss_PAR=6|loss_PAR=2|gf_PAR=59|ga_PAR=18\n|win_VOJ=19|PKwin_VOJ=4|PKloss_VOJ=1|loss_VOJ=9|gf_VOJ=45|ga_VOJ=31\n|win_OFK=19|PKwin_OFK=3|PKloss_OFK=5|loss_OFK=6|gf_OFK=62|ga_OFK=36\n|win_PRO=16|PKwin_PRO=3|PKloss_PRO=1|loss_PRO=13|gf_PRO=41|ga_PRO=43\n|win_VAR=15|PKwin_VAR=4|PKloss_VAR=2|loss_VAR=12|gf_VAR=50|ga_VAR=34\n|win_RAD=14|PKwin_RAD=1|PKloss_RAD=2|loss_RAD=16|gf_RAD=48|ga_RAD=43\n|win_BOR=11|PKwin_BOR=6|PKloss_BOR=4|loss_BOR=12|gf_BOR=24|ga_BOR=32\n|win_SAR=12|PKwin_SAR=3|PKloss_SAR=3|loss_SAR=14|gf_SAR=33|ga_SAR=45\n|win_ZEM=12|PKwin_ZEM=2|PKloss_ZEM=5|loss_ZEM=14|gf_ZEM=44|ga_ZEM=43\n|win_RNI=12|PKwin_RNI=2|PKloss_RNI=3|loss_RNI=16|gf_RNI=37|ga_RNI=48\n|win_BUD=10|PKwin_BUD=3|PKloss_BUD=5|loss_BUD=15|gf_BUD=30|ga_BUD=32\n|win_SNI=11|PKwin_SNI=1|PKloss_SNI=5|loss_SNI=16|gf_SNI=40|ga_SNI=47\n|win_VEL=10|PKwin_VEL=3|PKloss_VEL=2|loss_VEL=17|gf_VEL=34|ga_VEL=53\n|win_PEL=9|PKwin_PEL=2|PKloss_PEL=1|loss_PEL=21|gf_PEL=30|ga_PEL=57\n|win_SPA=7|PKwin_SPA=3|PKloss_SPA=6|loss_SPA=17|gf_SPA=24|ga_SPA=49\n|win_SLO=7|PKwin_SLO=2|PKloss_SLO=1|loss_SLO=21|gf_SLO=21|ga_SLO=61\n|win_\u017dEL=6|PKwin_\u017dEL=3|PKloss_\u017dEL=0|loss_\u017dEL=8|gf_\u017dEL=18|ga_\u017dEL=24\n|col_R=red1\n|result6=R|result9=R|result14=R|result15=R|result17=R|result18=R\n|update=complete\n|class_rules=1) points; 2) goal difference; 3) number of goals scored.\n|source=[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeg92.html rsssf.com] \n}}</onlyinclude>\nLeague topscorer: [[Darko Pan\u010dev]] (Red Star) '''25 goals''' from 28 league appearances\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Champions: [[Red Star Belgrade]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Player || colspan=2 | League\n|-\n! Matches||Goals\n|-\n| [[Du\u0161ko Radinovi\u0107]] || 30 || 4\n|-\n| [[Vladimir Jugovi\u0107]] || 29 || 4\n|-\n| [[Ilija Najdoski]] || 29 || 2\n|-\n| [[Darko Pan\u010dev]] || 28 || 25\n|-\n| [[Ilija Ivi\u0107]] || 27 || 8\n|-\n| [[Milorad Ratkovi\u0107]] || 26 || 4\n|-\n| [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]] || 24 || 8\n|-\n| [[Miodrag Belodedici]] || 24 || 1\n|-\n| [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107]] || 22 || 5\n|-\n| [[Miroslav Tanjga]] || 18 || 0\n|-\n| [[Vlada Sto\u0161i\u0107]] || 17 || 4\n|-\n| [[Dragoje Lekovi\u0107]] (goalkeeper) || 17 || 0  \n|-\n| [[Goran Vasilijevi\u0107]] || 15 || 0\n|-\n| [[Vladan Luki\u0107]] || 13 || 7\n|-\n| [[Zvonko Milojevi\u0107]] (goalkeeper) || 13 || 0  \n|-\n| [[Elvir Boli\u0107]] {{efn|arrived from [[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik Zenica]] in December 1991}} || 11 || 2 \n|-\n| [[Sa\u0161a Nedeljkovi\u0107 (footballer)|Sa\u0161a Nedeljkovi\u0107]] || 9 || 0\n|-\n| [[Slavi\u0161a \u010cula]] || 8 || 0\n|-\n| [[Mitko Stojkovski]] || 7 || 0\n|-\n| [[Du\u0161ko Savi\u0107]] || 5 || 0\n|-\n|